snippet.textDisplay:
---
So basically if this was/would be part of "Gadget Reviews"
( and it sort of is; this whole "thing"-process just required more through and varied testing hence a separate full-video),
the end-question would be something like this:
"Would I really be willing to spend 90-British-Sterling-Pounds(£) for essentially a semi-functional and very loud electric-pipette that gets clogged very easily and certainly is not easy to clean?
And even without the "pipette", would I want to make "pea-balls" out of everything?"

I personal answers:
"No way", for the "pipette".

"Yes" for the "pea-pearls"; they're a fancy "decorative-treats".
Though the process certainly needs to be better:
The "caviar" needs to the full-taste instead of being super-diluted/watered-down in a "eugh"-additive-heavy-chemical-soup.

---
---

Randomly inspired rant:
So this is one of those "English"-videos in which I (finally) realize-learn yet another without-any-actual-leads-made-up-word in English-vocabulary
(well, kind of, but it still is one):
"Sodium"
Chemical symbol is "Na" from Latin "Natrium".
"Sodium" is derivation from Italian "slang"-word "soda" which derives from arabic-word "sawād" which in English is "saltwort(?)"
(a "?" because that "etymology-chain" is the only one that would make somewhat sense to me, since "soda"-word alone would mean "splitting headache" according some translations).
"-ium"-suffix being just an addition to define the chemical-element being "metallic" (<- due "ferrum ("iron")")

This is yet another entry to go with into the English-exclusive-"Because why not"-dictionary to accompany words "pineapple ("ananas")" / "Naples ("Napoli / Neapolis")" and maybe some others which I've yet to "catch on".

(( Seriously though, I have yet to find any information why and where English even came up with the name "Naples";
like were English just so pissed about "Napoleon Bonaparte" and have gone all this effort to avoid saying his name that they actually "renamed" an Italian city just out of spite due since Northern Italia was called as "Napoleonic Kingdom of Italy" during the "French-Reign"?..

...Well okay, I guess it is possibly also a "bastardization / corruption"-word from "Neapolis" which from Greek-language would simply mean "new city".))
((( And yes, I am leaving these "Italia-typos" intact because I am not English! )))

---
To be fair, for example Finnish-language also has many made-up words:
Chemistry-wise there is
- "happi ("oxygen")" which derives from word "hapan ("acidic")"
( but then again, most of the corrosion-processes requires oxygen to begin with )
- "vety ("hydrogen")" deriving from "vesi ("water")" because that's basically same naming-scheme Lavoisier(?) used
("hydrogen" in Latin means "water-former / water-creator", referencing to water being the burning product of hydrogen)
- "rikki ("sulphur")" is a big oddity since it same as "broken" in Finnish;
aside for the regional dialects some which refers to "rheum (mucus)" and "(ear) wax" due the similar colour, possibility also is the reference to how easily sulphur immolates and burns, I.E. it is essentially "already and always broken"
---
---
